<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Progress at Georgian-Abkhaz Talks in Geneva </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402171594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1145 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402171594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Two working groups to develop drafts of the final 
document and agreement on refugees have been formed at the third 
round of the Georgian-Abkhazian negotiations underway in Geneva, 
the press center of Abkhazia's plenipotentiary representative to 
Russia reported to INTERFAX. 
  According to the press center, leader of the Georgian 
delegation Jaba Ioseliani accused the Abkhazian side of waging 
"ethnic cleansing" in Abkhazia's Gali Region and said that "the 
Abkhazians respect only the language of force." He expressed 
doubt with respect to further continuation of the negotiations. 
Leader of the Abkhazian delegation Premier Sokrat Dzhindzholia 
rejected Ioseliani's assertions and called them "insulting." 
  Meanwhile, member of the Georgian delegation Irakly 
Makhavariani reported in his interview with the Georgian TV on 
Thursday [24 February] that two days of the negotiations were 
fruitless. In his words, the parties are coordinating the 
document to return refugees to Abkhazia. Machavariani pointed 
out that the parties occupy controversial positions on this 
issue, that's why "it is difficult to find common approaches." 
  He did not rule out that negotiations to be concluded 
February 24 would be continued on February 25 because, to quote 
Machavariani, "there is a certain advance in the position of the 
Abkhazian party." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

