<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Hopes for `Certain Consensus' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402214694 Tbilisi CONTACT INFORMATION AGENCY in Russian 
1530 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2402214694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi CONTACT INFORMATION AGENCY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] We had a telephone conversation today with Irakli 
Machavariani, a member of the Georgian delegation at the Geneva 
talks on settling the Abkhazian conflict. He reported that the 
Abkhazian party had put forward a concept of Abkhazia's legal 
statute that is absolutely unacceptable for Georgia. It 
stipulates "not even a confederative restructuring within the 
frame of an integral Georgia but rather a form of a treaty much 
more resembling relations between two neighbor states, in 
addition, rather cool." 
  Machavariani particularly pointed out that the Abkhazian 
party behaves as a "victor" in the light of recent events in 
Gali Rayon and this causes extreme aggravation in the atmosphere 
of the talks. 
  However, said Machavariani, representatives of the world 
community and Russia at the talks keep backing an idea of 
Georgia's territorial integrity and in this respect their 
position is quite close to that of Georgia. This permits us to 
pin hopes on reaching a certain consensus while handling the 
problem. 
  According to Machavariani, a concluding sitting will be held 
tomorrow, when the work carried out at the talks will be summed 
up. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

