<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Polish Delegation Arrives, Meets With Officials </TI></H3>
<H4>   Walesa on NATO Aspirations </H4>
<F P=102> LD2402180994 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1500 
GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2402180994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Poland and Latvia have similar views on issues most 
important to both countries. This was stated at a news 
conference of the Polish and Latvian presidents in Riga. 
  According to President Guntis Ulmanis, Poland as the largest 
country in the region could become a guarantor for the unity of 
the Baltic states. Imperial voices in Russia pose a real 
threat, it was said at the conference. 
  Asked to comment on Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev's 
statement that the states of Central Europe should consider 
their aspirations toward NATO, Lech Walesa replied: We have 
already done that. I suggest Kozyrev should consider it and not 
hamper our intentions. 
  According to Walesa the West does not know about a large 
concentration of Russian troops in Kaliningrad Oblast. One has 
to ask publicly, what purpose is it serving, how much does it 
cost and who is threatened by it. 
  During his visit to Riga, President Walesa today visited the 
Latvian Saeima and met its speaker. He also continued talks 
with the Latvian president and met Latvian defense and foreign 
affairs ministers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

