<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Snegur Says Dniester Should Be Given Special Legal Status </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402230694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1711 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402230694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature No. 38 (528) by </F>
diplomatic correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, 
Vitaliy Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] President Mircea Snegur has said he will take all 
measures so that the forthcoming parliamentary elections 
February 27 pass democratically with the entire republic's 
population taking part. At the meeting in Chisinau Wednesday 
with the U.S. Ambassador Mary Pendleton he said that only a 
competent and constructive parliament may further develop the 
process of reforms, whose success will elevate the living 
standards of the population. 
  A spokesman for the president has told Interfax that the 
head 
of state voiced confidence that the problem of Transdniester 
could be solved if the region is granted the special legal 
status. Snegur said that President Yeltsin had said about the 
preparedness to be a mediator at the talks to settle the 
conflict on the basis of recommendations by the CSCE standing 
mission. 
  Snegur has confirmed his intention to propose to the new 
parliament bills on granting a special status for the region of 
the left bank of the Dniester and for that densely populated by 
the Gagauz people. 
  Less than one thousand Transdniestrians took part since the 
beginning of the week in the parliamentary elections in Moldova. 
According to Snegur's decree, inhabitants of the Transdniestrian 
Republic are allowed to vote on February 21-27 at the polling 
stations on the right bank of the Dniester. 
  A spokesman for the Central Election Commission has told 
Interfax, the authorities of the Transdniestrian Republic put no 
serious obstacles to the people living on the left bank. The 
Central Election Commission explains the low activeness of 
voters by the shortage of transport for carrying people from the 
left to the right bank, as well as by the fact there is still 
time for taking part in the voting. 

</TEXT>

