<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Elections Marred by `Gross Irregularities' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402164494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1330 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402164494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Chisinau February 24 TASS--Moldovan opposition 
parties favouring unification with Romania received, in defiance 
of law, financial assistance from Bucharest for their 
campaigning ahead of the February 27 parliamentary elections, a 
leader of Moldova's Agrarian Democratic Party, Nicolae Andronik, 
claimed here today. 
  According to him, once being launched, the election campaign 
has been marred with gross irregularities of the election law 
banning any assistance from abroad to parties running for the 
forthcoming elections. In particular, Andronik said, at the 
polling station in the village of Varnica, which opened a week 
earlier for voters of Moldova's breakaway Dniester region, the 
local administration head instructed residents how to vote for 
opposition parties. 
  Moldovan parliamentary chairman Pyotr Luchinskiy expressed 
regret that the election campaign is blemished with breaches of 
law and ethic norms by the opposition, "which seeks to regain 
its popularity by these means". He did not rule out that the 
Central Electoral Commission largely consisting of 
representatives of opposition parties would not approve voting 
results if Moldova's Agrarian Democratic Party won the elections. 
  In this case, Luchinskiy stressed, the Supreme Court will 
have the final say. And the court has already cancelled the 
ruling by the Central Electoral Commission not to open polling 
stations in Gagauz-dominated areas for fear that residents there 
might vote for the Agrarian Democratic Party. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

