<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gamsakhurdia Buried in Groznyy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402192794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1603 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402192794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sharip Asuyev] </F>
  [Text] Groznyy February 24 TASS -- Georgian ex-President 
Zviad Gamsakhurdia was buried on Thursday in the Russian 
break-away Republic of Chechnya. The funeral ceremony was 
attended by Chechen President General Dzhokhar Dudayev. 
  Georgia's first popularly-elected president was buried on 
the 
territory of his residence in Groznyy, where he spent most of 
his political exile after being toppled in January 1992. 
  Last autumn, Gamsakhurdia returned to western Georgia in a 
quest to restore his presidential status, but his supporters 
were ousted from Georgia by the Army, which stood loyal to the 
existing Tbilisi government of Eduard Shevardnadze. 
  Gamsakhurdia then reportedly took his life after being 
cornered by his enemies in a west Georgian village. 
  Last Thursday, Gamsakhurdia's body was exhumated and 
air-lifted to Groznyy from western Georgia, where it had been 
temporarily buried in a secret place under a village barn by his 
close lieutenants. It was reburied here in conformity with the 
will of his next of kin. As Gamsakhurdia's widow Manana put it, 
the funeral in Tbilisi "would be most likely used by his enemies 
in their political aims." 
  So Gamsakhurdia was finally buried with full military 
honours 
and now rests in peace. But for how long? His relatives and 
supporters join in the hope that the time will come when the 
remnants of the president are buried with all due honours in his 
motherland. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

