<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dudayev Accuses Moscow of Destabilizing Situation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402170494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1145 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402170494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev has again accused 
Moscow of a desire to destabilize the situation in his republic, 
namely of provoking opposition forces for anti-government 
disturbances. He described such Russian attempts as futile and 
said that the Chechen leadership controls the situation in the 
republic. Dudayev warned of a fair punishment for all 
encroachments against the Chechen people. 
  Dudayev addressed a news conference on Wednesday night in 
Groznyy following the commemoration devoted to the 50th 
anniversary of the deportation of the Chechen people. We shall 
not forget 600,000 victims of deportation and 40,000 of those 
who died in the Great Patriotic War, he said. 
  The Chechen president welcomed the Russian Duma's resolution 
on political amnesty of those involved in the developments of 
1991 and 1993 and called it a "just" action. At the same time, 
Dudayev voiced doubt that the amnesty would be fulfilled. 
  Answering the questions about the fate of the Georgian 
ex-president Zviad Gamsakhurdia, who shot himself dead in the 
early hours of January 1, 1994, Dudayev noted the valuable role 
he played in the social and political life of Georgia and the 
Caucasus as a whole. Dudayev said that Gamsakhurdia acted in a 
noble way when he understood that further struggle would lead to 
a national catastrophe in Georgia and decided to commit suicide. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

