<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Calls For Joining Nonproliferation Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502121494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1123 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502121494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk sent a message 
to parliament Thursday calling for joining the 1968 Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty. 
  Anton Buteiko, the president's foreign affairs adviser, told 
Interfax-Ukraine that this message, the third of this kind in as 
many years, presented new arguments in favor of joining the 
treaty that follow from the trilateral communique of the U.S., 
Ukrainian and Russian presidents and the Western response to it. 
That communique provided for the nuclear disarmament of Ukraine. 
  "The president says that parliament should speed up making a 
decision," the adviser said. He emphasized that a speedy 
decision would be in Ukraine's interests. 
  The Ukrainian parliament ratified START-1 and Article 5 of 
the Lisbon protocol whereby Ukraine undertakes to join the 
Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty as a non-nuclear state. 
Parliament did not, however, join the treaty immediately. Its 
Speaker Ivan Plyushch told journalists in early February that 
"joining the 1968 Treaty will be debated by a new parliament." 

</TEXT>

