<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Actions Pending on Unauthorized Russian Military Transit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2402200994 Tallinn BNS in English 1548 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2402200994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Feb 24, BNS -- Lithuanian Foreign Ministry 
and Defense Ministry officials meet Thursday [24 February] to 
decide on further actions if Russia attempts to carry out 
unauthorized military transit through Lithuanian territory, said 
Lieutenant Colonel Algirdas Jurkevicius. 
  Inspector Jurkevicius heads the Defense Ministry's dangerous 
cargo transportation division and is authorized to issue or to 
deny permissions for Russian military transit. 
  On Tuesday, he instructed Lithuanian railroad officials to 
stop a Russian train with around 30 armored personnel carriers, 
which were escorted by four armed Russian soldiers. 
  The train was allowed to enter Lithuanian territory from the 
Kaliningrad region late Tuesday when 17 flatcars with military 
equipment were disconnected. 
  The leadership of the Russian troops stationed in 
Kaliningrad 
apologized for an incident last weekend when a Russian echelon 
crossed the Lithuanian border without any permission of 
Lithuanian authorities. 
  On Tuesday, Russian Army officials requested a transit 
permission for a new echelon but Jurkevicius denied their 
request. 
  Jurkevicius said his decision was prompted by the media's 
strong reaction to the incident last weekend. 
  Until now, Russian military transit from Kaliningrad was 
reportedly carried out in accordance with the rules of transit 
from Germany. Apparently, the inspector is no longer willing to 
apply the same rules to transit from Kaliningrad and to transit 
from Germany. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

