<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Adviser Denies Government Wants U.S. Navy on Caspian Sea </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402151594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1145 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tulegen Zhukeyev, Kazakhstan's state adviser, 
rejected information stating that the republic's leadership 
advocates U.S. military presence on the Caspian Sea. In the 
course of Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev's visit to the 
United States from February 13-17 "the parties did not even 
raise this issue," Zhukeyev reported in his interview with 
Interfax on Thursday. 
  The adviser voiced this statement due to the assertions of 
the Iranian admiral Ali Shamakhin who declared in his interview 
with the Tehran newspaper Dzhumkhurne Islami early this week 
that Kazakhstan invites the Americans to ensure an American 
military presence on the Caspian Sea. 
  Zhukeyev underlined that Kazakhstan does not plan to bring 
about the presence of American naval forces or involvement of 
Americans as military advisers on the Caspian Sea. At the same 
time he did not rule out the possibility that the republic's 
leadership would address the United States for consultation 
concerning creation of Kazakhstan's coast guard service on the 
Caspian Sea. "Americans have great experience in this sphere and 
currently Kazakhstan faces these problems with respect to the 
Caspian Sea," said Zhukeyev. 
  The state adviser also reported that at present, the Kazakh 
and Russian governments are defining plans to jointly guard CIS 
sea border on the Caspian Sea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

