<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Envoy Says UN Knows Nothing of Concentration Camps </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302190294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1310 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302190294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridneva] </F>
  [Text] Dushanbe February 23 TASS -- A UN envoy in 
Tajikistan said he knows nothing about the alleged existence of 
concentration camps in the Central Asian republic where 
opposition members are being kept, but added that the 
information needs a thorough check. 
  "We do not have any facts about the existence of 
concentration camps in Tajikistan", Liviu Botha, head of the UN 
mission in Tajikistan, told reporters on Wednesday commenting on 
corresponding Western mass media reports which claimed that 
political prisoners are being kept in three major camps on Tajik 
territory. 
  However, Botha confirmed that he had received the 
information 
and added that it needs to be thoroughly checked. 
  He stressed that the Tajik Government agreed to render any 
necessary assistance to the UN mission in inspecting the 
mentioned areas were the camps are allegedly situated. 
  Tajik Parliament Speaker Imamali Rakhmonov categorically 
denied in an interview to TASS the alleged existence in the 
country of concentration camps and of political prisoners. 
  One of the leaders of the Security Ministry qualified the 
reports as "dirty insinuations". 
  The news also caused open confusion among foreign and 
Russian 
correspondents accredited in Tajikistan who said they had heard 
nothing about any concentration camps. 

</TEXT>

