<DATE1>  25 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Turkmenistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Azerbaijan To Receive Gas; Ukraine Supply Cut Off </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402164794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1616 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402164794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Lyudmila Glazovskaya and Oleg </F>
Lukin] 
  [Text] Ashgabat February 24 TASS -- Turkmenistan is to 
supply this year 3 billion cubic meters of natural gas to 
Azerbaijan. An agreement to this effect was concluded during 
the recent vivit by Azerbaijan's official delegation to the 
Central Asian republic. The document was signed between the 
Turkmennebitgasexport organization and the Azerigas state-run 
company. 
  The agreement provides for clearing payments in hard 
currency. The contracting sides settled the price at the level 
of 80 dollars for 1,000 cubic meters of gas, transport carges 
inclusive. Azerbaijan is to supply Turkmenistan with industrial 
equipment, consumer goods and foodstuffs for the sum equivalent 
to the value of gas supplies. 
  As for gas supplies to Ukraine, Turkmen Oil and Gas Minister 
Nazar Suyunov [title as received] confirmed they had been fully 
discontinued because of unpaid debts. However, it does not mean 
that Turkmenistan rejects any counter proposals, he stressed. 
The republic is ready to consider them on any positive basis. 
Suyunov noted Ukraine's commercial structures are willing to 
cooperate but they cannot do this bypassing state-run 
organizations resolutely determined not to pay off their debts. 
Once, the minister explained, Turkmenistan offered clearing 
settlements to Ukraine, but the latter turned down the offer. 
Now it also refuses to honour its bills. 
  According to the Turkmen minister, such an approach is 
rather 
surprising, to say the least. However, Turkmenistan is still 
ready to search for mutually acceptable solutions, which is 
proved by its agreements with Georgia and Azerbaijan, Suyunov 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

