<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Urges Approval of Additional Troops for Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402172894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1501 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402172894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: reports by </F>
Diplomatic Correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboinikov, Igor Porshnev, 
Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and others] 
  [Text] President Yeltsin has urged the Federation Council 
to endorse the dispatch of an additional military contingent 
numbering 300 men to join the U.N. peace-keeping forces in 
former Yugoslavia "with a view to ensuring control over the 
implementation of an agreement on a peaceful solution to the 
conflict, and over the unconditional observance of the agreement 
to cease fire in the area of Sarajevo by the warring sides". 
  The Russian president made this appeal in connection with a 
request from the U.N. Secretary General. The relevant draft 
resolution instructs Russia's government to resolve the issues 
connected with the forming of a corresponding volunteer military 
contingent. 
  The Federation Council decided to consider this issue in the 
framework of its defence and security committee Friday morning, 
and discuss it at its evening session the same day. 

</TEXT>

