<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev on Policy in Bosnia, NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402172694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1501 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402172694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: Reports by </F>
diplomatic correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, 
Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and others] 
  [Text] Moscow has no intention of taking the side of any 
party involved in the conflict in former Yugoslavia, said the 
head of Russian diplomacy, Andrey Kozyrev, upon his return from 
a trip to Greece, the Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland. 
  "The essence of Russian initiative is to nudge Bosnia's 
warring sides toward a peaceful solution to the problem," he 
told Russian journalists who accompanied him. "Russia must use 
its historically established ties with the Serbs to nudge them 
toward dialogue, not to encourage aggression." 
  The issue of Russia's policy toward the former Eastern bloc 
countries cropped up more than once during his conversations in 
European capitals. Kozyrev assured his partners in the talks 
that Moscow is nurturing no "imperial plans", that it is 
prepared "to cooperate with everyone on the basis of 
neighborliness and mutual benefit". 
  According to him, the intention of Central and East European 
countries to join NATO is no obstacle to this. "We do not rule 
out the possibility that Russia will also become part of NATO 
some time, but today the idea of partnership is of key 
importance," Kozyrev stressed. 
  In this context NATO's "Partnership for Peace" program 
acquires special importance, the head of Russian diplomacy said. 
"There is a need to create a system of "cross-guarantees" by 
means of signing corresponding agreements with each European 
state separately," he said. 
  Wednesday morning, addressing a conference on the prospects 
for Russian-Polish relations in Krakow, Kozyrev formulated 
Russia's concept of European partnership, which provides for 
transforming the Conference for Security and Cooperation in 
Europe (CSCE) into an "effective regional political 
organization, and the North-Atlantic Council for Cooperation 
into an independent structure of politico-military cooperation 
closely connected with the CSCE. 
  When asked about his attitude to the Liberal Democratic 
Party 
and its leader, Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, Kozyrev said: "I 
instructed the Foreign Ministry's press service to neither read 
what Zhirinovskiy says, nor react to it". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

