<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO General Praises Training of Troops Sent to Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402164694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1343 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 24 TASS--Good military training of 
Russian commandos shown during their redisposition to the 
Sarajevo region was highly estimated by NATO generals, deputy 
supreme commander of the NATO Joint Armed Forces in Europe, 
General John Waters, who arrived in Moscow on a working visit 
today, told ITAR-TASS. 
  The NATO commander who prior to his appointment to a high 
post in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization headed the land 
forces in Britain, said he envied his colleague in Bosnia who 
had received such a powerful and well trained reinforcement. 
  Speaking on the difficulties connected with the 
redisposition 
of the Russian blue helmets, John Waters noted that he knew that 
Russian commandos' training was passing in much more complex 
conditions, therefore he would rather be surprised if Russian 
soldiers and officers had not fulfilled their command's order. 
  The British General highly appraised Russia's efforts aimed 
at settling the armed conflict in Bosnia and stressed that the 
NATO welcomed any step which would stop killing people. 
  John Waters noted that air strikes, as the events in the 
Persian Gulf had shown, would have resulted in unjustified 
victims amongst the civil population. 
  The general said that additional peacekeeping forces should 
be brought to the region of confrontation specifying that this 
problem should be resolved by politicians. 
  The program of the NATO general's visit to Moscow which will 
last until February 26, includes his meetings with the 
leadership of the General Staff of the Russian Armed Forces and 
the commander-in-chief of the land forces. 
  John Waters will also deliver several lectures on the theme 
"The NATO Bloc in a Stage of Transformation" to students and 
teachers of the Academy of the General Staff, and other 
institutions of the Russian Defense Ministry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

