<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Foreign Ministry Statement on Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2402112594 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 24 Feb 94 
First Edition p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PM2402112594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under "Distant Foreign Parts" rubric: </F>
"Moscow Calls for Pressure To Be Exerted on the Bosnian 
Government"] 
  [Text] Russia is urging the United States and the European 
Union [EU] to "exert the necessary influence over the Bosnian 
Government to make it cooperate with the United Nations in the 
matter of completely unblocking and demilitarizing Sarajevo. 
[no closing quotation mark as published] This is stated in a 
Russian Federation Foreign Ministry statement disseminated at 
the United Nations 22 February as a Security Council document, 
ITAR-TASS reports. 
  "In recent days," the document points out, "Russia has 
undertaken additional efforts to realize its initiative with 
regard to unblocking Sarajevo and transferring this city to UN 
control, which it advanced back at the 47th General Assembly 
Session. We have sought and are seeking to implement this 
initiative by acting openly within the framework of Security 
Council resolutions." 
  It points out that "as a result of the steps taken by the 
leadership of Russia and intensive diplomatic work, this firm 
and consistent line, which rules out unilateral ultimatums, has 
produced a result." "In response to our appeal the Bosnian 
Serbs adopted a decision at their assembly in Pale to withdraw 
their heavy arms from the Sarajevo reigon. We reckon that this 
show of goodwill by one of the sides involved in the conflict at 
a critical moment for a settlement will elicit equally specific 
countersteps.... We also urge our partners in the Bosnian 
settlement -- above all, the United States and the EU countries 
-- in the spirit of their statements on the preferability of a 
political solution to the problem, to exert the necessary 
influence over the Bosnian Government to make it cooperate with 
the United Nations in the matter of completely unblocking and 
demilitarizing Sarajevo," the statement reads. 
  Russia has proposed that, following the unblocking of 
Sarajevo, the UN Security Council urgently begin examining ways 
to establish an administration in this city, as well as measures 
to strengthen other safe areas on the territory of Bosnia and 
Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

