<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Adamishin, Japanese Official Meet, Discuss G-7 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402195194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1705 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402195194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian First Deputy Foreign Minister Anatoliy 
Adamishin and Japanese Deputy Foreign Minister Hiroshi Fukuda, 
who met in Moscow Wednesday, expressed the desire of both 
countries to expand political and other contacts and to improve 
the atmosphere of partnership, confidence and good neighborly 
relations. 
  According to Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Grigoriy 
Karasin, Russia's joining the G-7 group of most advanced 
countries would open up new vistas for cooperation in 
international issues. 
  He told journalists that the Japanese official wanted to 
have 
a better insight into the political situation in Russia. 
"Unambiguous remarks made by President Boris Yeltsin and Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin were quoted to show that Russia 
will stay on the reform course," Karasin said. 

</TEXT>

