<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Duma Decision on Amnesty for Prisoners </TI></H3>
<H4>   Court Says Yeltsin Lacks Veto Authority </H4>
<F P=102> LD2402173494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1502 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402173494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  A Russian Constitutional Court source said the president 
has neither the authority nor the moral right to veto the 
amnesty resolution passed by the State Duma, the lower house of 
parliament. 
  The source, who asked not to be identified, told Interfax 
that, under the Constitution, the resolution is not subject to 
approval by either the upper house of the legislature or the 
president. The resolution is thus definitive and cannot be 
revised, but theoretically it can be checked by the 
Constitutional Court, the source said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

