<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Duma Decision on Amnesty for Prisoners </TI></H3>
<H4>   Defendants To Decide on Amnesty </H4>
<F P=102> LD2402224194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1705 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402224194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Deputy of the Council of Federation, one of the 
defendants in the State of Emergency Committee case told 
Interfax on Thursday that all those accused on that case will 
take a joint decision whether they will take advantage of the 
amnesty declared by the State Duma the day before. 
  "Neither I, nor my comrades, have not committed any crime in 
August of 1991. We were defending the Constitution of the USSR 
and trying to rescue the country from collapse and death. An 
amnesty is applied to criminals, and we are not criminals," 
Starodubtsev said. 
  At the same time, he called the State Duma resolution on the 
amnesty "a courageous step" showing that "the Duma will not be 
obedient." 

</TEXT>

