<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Duma Decision on Amnesty for Prisoners </TI></H3>
<H4>   Prisoner Release Delayed </H4>
<F P=102> LD2402202894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1901 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Those arrested for their part in the Moscow riots of 
October 3 and 4 will not be released tonight. 
  The attorneys of some of them told Interfax that the 
investigators explained the delay by saying that the State Duma 
decision to declare amnesty on February 23 had to be first 
published in newspapers. Only then will they show the text to 
the accused and ask if they accept the amnesty. 
  Numerous attorneys do not rule out the possibility that some 
of the detainees who do not feel they are guilty of organizing 
riots will reject the offer of release. Under the existing 
legislation those charged with criminal offenses are pardoned by 
the state but are not rehabilitated for their activities which 
are regarded as criminal by the investigators. 
  Larisa Dementyeva, the attorney of Aleksandr Barkashov, 
leader of the Russian National Unity, said that her client would 
most probably agree to be pardoned. She emphasized Barkashov 
was in poor health following several surgeries for a wound he 
had received last December. He is now in the medical ward of 
Matrosskaya Tishina investigating prison and will most probably 
be hospitalized Friday. 
  Dmitry Shteinberg, the attorney of former security minister 
Viktor Barannikov, told Interfax that his client had left the 
hospital for home. He had undertaken not to leave the city. 
The doctors insist that he is too sick to be questioned. 
  Meanwhile, the Izvestiya daily reports that Vyacheslav 
Kostikov, Russian president's press secretary, said outside the 
Federal Assembly hall Thursday that nobody will leave Lefortovo 
or Matrosskaya Tishina prisons in the coming weeks, if not 
months. He described the amnesty as immoral because the 
detainees had blood on their hands. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

