<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Duma Decision on Amnesty for Prisoners </TI></H3>
<H4>   Defendants Awaiting Text of Decree </H4>
<F P=102> LD2402154894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1517 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Olga Colodova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 24 TASS -- Aleksandr Barkashov, 
leader of the Russian National Unity Nazi-inspired organisation, 
will not refuse the amnesty offered by the State Duma (the lower 
chamber of the Russian parliament) on Wednesday, if it applies 
to him. Barkashov's men took an active part in the hard-line 
revolt last October. ITAR-TASS learned of Barkoshov's 
intentions on Thursday through his lawyer, Larisa Dementyeva. 
  Dementyeva also announced that, according to Article Five of 
the criminal procedural code of the Russian Federation, "The 
application of an amnesty should not depend on whether or not 
the accused has confessed to the charges filed against him". 
  The lawyers of other participants in the October 3-4 events 
refused, when asked by ITAR-TASS, to make any statements until 
they receive the official text of the anmesty from the State 
Duma. Procurator-General of Russia Aleksey Kazannik has promised 
to distribute the text to the concerned defenders as soon as it 
is forwarded to his office. 

</TEXT>

