<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Luzhkov Expresses Mixed Views of Yeltsin Address </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402164994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1145 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The President's message to parliament is an 
absolutely new form of political life in Russia, Moscow's Mayor 
Yuriy Luzhkov told Interfax. 
  I believe, said Luzhkov, there are two important problems in 
the message: the combating of crime and the stabilization of 
the economy. These two problems must be solved as early as 
possible and to do so available forces should be used 
efficiently. 
  The Mayor said he was completely unsatisfied by the words 
said by the president about privatization. 
  The problem should have had more emphasis in the message. 
The state has received nothing from the voucher privatization 
campaign: neither money nor a new owner. The completion of the 
campaign means a failure for the Russian economy, said Luzhkov. 
  The Moscow Mayor believes that the president did right when 
in his message he spoke about the protection of the 
Russian-speakers in the CIS countries. 
  I have just returned from Sevastopol and I am alarmed by the 
fact that the forceful "Ukrainization" of the Russians is taking 
place there. There are 75 percent of Russians living in the 
city. I intend to report to the president about this, he said. 
  The Moscow Mayor said that if in such historically Russian 
cities as Sevastopol and Narva, Russian residents are being 
forced to take on an alien life style, culture, language and 
their rights are infringed upon, the problem could develop from 
a diplomatic one to one with grave social and political 
consequences. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

