<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lavrov Calls Ames Case `Washington's Internal Affair' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402174294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1501 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402174294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: Reports by </F>
diplomatic correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboinikov, Igor Porshnev, 
Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and others] 
  [Text] The detention of the CIA member Aldrich Ames and his 
wife Maria on charges of spying in favor of Moscow is 
Washington's internal affair, Russia's Deputy Foreign Minister, 
Sergey Lavrov, told Interfax on Thursday [24 February]. This is 
his personal assessment of what happened, he noted. 
  "This is a problem for the Americans. They detained their 
own citizen, a CIA member, and they must deal with him in 
accordance with their own laws. Instead of it high-ranking U.S. 
officials have said, before trial, that this incident may have 
an impact on Russian-American relations. We do not quite 
understand it," Lavrov said. 
  The U.S. secretary of state, Warren Christopher, has already 
told Senate that he has no intention of commenting on events 
that concern America's intelligence work, he noted. "He can 
comment on other country's intelligence work, but not on that of 
America. Following this logic I must refrain from commenting on 
our activity, the more so as I do not see our activity in this 
case. What I see is that they arrested their own man. But this 
is their own problem. Let their court of law consider the 
charges against Ames," Lavrov said. 
  He finds it hard to say why this incident "surfaced" right 
now. "Judging by what U.S. officials say, they have been dealing 
with this business for a long time. It's not quite clear why 
they decided to sort it out right now. This was a step taken by 
the American side, and we learned about it after the fact," the 
diplomat said. 
  Lavrov was skeptical about the supposition that "the Ameses 
case" is a kind of "retaliation" for Russia's political efforts 
to resolve the crisis in Bosnia. "It's hard to imagine that the 
Americans decided to "avenge themselves" on Russia in this way. 
This would have been too petty," Lavrov said. 
  With reference to his Tuesday's meeting with the U.S. 
ambassador to Moscow, Thomas Pickering, the diplomat said that 
the ambassador had only handed him written information 
concerning Washington's reaction to the Ameses incident. "We 
accepted it and promised to study it in detail," Russia's deputy 
foreign minister said. 
  It's essential to avoid "emotions and overdramatization" in 
connection with the Ameses case, said the Director of the 
Foreign Ministry's press and information department, Grigoriy 
Karasin, at Thursday's briefing. 
  The Foreign Ministry received information concerning this 
through "official channels", he said. "However there are many 
serious questions that need to be analysed before making any 
conclusions," Karasin noted. 
  According to him, this should be dealt with by professionals 
from Russian and American secret services. "Contacts between 
them are well established. The main thing is to settle the 
incident without political or diplomatic complications and avoid 
kindling passions," the spokesman for Russia's Foreign Ministry 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38034 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov038_b_94012" </HT>


