<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lavrov Comments `Skeptically' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402220794 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
2020 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2402220794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Excerpts] Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov has 
commented skeptically on the idea that the Ames affair might be 
a response to the political activity displayed by Russia in 
resolving the Bosnian crisis. Foreign Ministry spokesman 
Grigoriy Karasin said today that it was important to avoid 
emotional and overdramatized attitudes and that it was necessary 
to analyze the situation before drawing any conclusions. 
  At the same time experts continue commenting on the 
situation 
from very different angles. Here is a report by Andrey 
Pishchayev. 
  [Pishchayev] Recently, a similar incident occurred between 
the United States and Israel but the scandal promptly died down. 
On this occasion, however, the American side is talking about a 
great detriment to its national interests and has nearly started 
wondering whether it ought to continue its friendship with 
Russia. [passage omitted] 
  Many questions arise in connection with this scandal. CIA 
staff had been closely watching the Moscow agent for two years, 
so why did they choose to arrest him at this particular point? 
President Clinton knew about the forthcoming arrest when he was 
leaving for the Moscow summit with Boris Yeltsin. 
  [Begin V. Kremenyuk, deputy director of the Institute for 
U.S. and Canadian studies, recording] The fact that this 
incident emerged just now confirms that Clinton was not quite 
satisfied with the results of that summit, and that he was 
particularly displeased with the outcome of the recent crisis in 
Bosnia. [end recording] 
  According to Kremenyuk, the reasoning behind President 
Clinton's sanction of the spy's arrest went like this: 
  [Begin Kremenyuk recording] Let us make it clear that they 
[Russians] are no peacemakers but merely the same dirty spies 
that they always used to be. Let us create a small crisis that 
would enable us to put some pressure on Yeltsin. [end recording] 
  In the opinion of Russian diplomats, it would be too petty a 
revenge on Russia. Anyway, we can only guess why the Ames 
affair has emerged so unexpectedly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

