<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Gives News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Comments on Ames Affair </H4>
<F P=102> LD2402150494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1405 
GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2402150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Aleksandr Krylovich </F>
and Vladimir Taranov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 24 Feb--"All efforts must now be directed 
toward ensuring that the incident over the arrest of a CIA 
employee is settled without inflicting any significant political 
and diplomatic damage either to Russia or the United States". 
This was stated at a briefing today by Grigoriy Karasin, 
director of the Information and Press Department of the Russian 
Federation Foreign Ministry. 
  "The position of the Russian Federation Foreign Ministry in 
this question is pretty clear," he stressed. According to the 
Russian diplomat, the Foreign Ministry had been informed about 
the story regarding the arrest of a CIA member and his wife 
through official channels in Washington and Moscow. This whole 
story raises a great many serious questions that must be 
carefully and closely studied and analyzed. Clearly, it is the 
professionals--representatives of the special services of both 
states--who will play the leading role in this, Karasin noted. 
  Speaking about the political aspects of the incident, the 
Foreign Ministry spokesman stressed that here "it is important 
to avoid overdramatization and extreme political emotions". The 
Russian side intends to clear up this incident quickly and 
effectively, Karasin noted in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

