<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Georgia, Abkhazia Fail To Reach Accord at Geneva Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502192294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1615 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502192294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Konstantin Pribytkov] </F>
  [Text] Geneva February 25 TASS -- Georgian and Abkhazian 
delegations failed to reach an accord on key issues in the peace 
settlement between Tbilisi and its independence-seeking province 
during their four-day U.N.- and Russia-brokered meeting in 
Geneva. 
  The third round of talks, which ended on Friday, revealed at 
least two problems where a compromise is hardly possible. They 
are the future political status of Abkhazia and conditions for 
the return home of refugees. The draft agreements on both these 
problems remained unsigned. 
  The two sides agreed to renew negotiations in New York on 
March 7 on the proposal put forward by U.N. Secretary General's 
envoy Edward Brunner and backed by Russian envoy Boris Pastukhov. 
  Pastukhov told ITAR-TASS that he "regretted that the round 
of 
talks had not brought the desired result". 
  The only positive moment he could mention was the "motion 
towards a compromise" as both delegations confirmed that they 
welcomed the participation of the Russian military contingent in 
the UN peace- keeping operations in the conflict area. 

</TEXT>

