<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Intelligence Staffers on CIA Delegation in Moscow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502211894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2044 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502211894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By CRIME-PRESS correspondent Olga Semyonova] </F>
  [Text] Reliable sources reject U.S. media reports that the 
CIA delegation which negotiated with the Russian Foreign 
Intelligence Service on the "Ames case" has returned to the 
United States and is dissatisfied with the Russian reaction. 
  "As far as I know CIA representatives are still in Russia. 
They have met heads of the Russian Foreign Intelligence Service 
to discuss professional and technical issues. It seems the 
sides have managed to reach mutual understanding in some 
aspects," a veteran staffer of the Russian Foreign Intelligence 
Service who used to work in the United States told CRIME PRESS 
on Friday. 
  Commenting on the "Ames case" Russian intelligence officials 
remind that in similar situations Russians seldom make fuss. 
Last year twenty people were arrested in Russia on espionage 
charge, according to First Deputy Director of the Russian 
Counter-Intelligence Service Sergey Stepashin. However, there 
were no scandals, demarches or loud protesting, as professionals 
can control their emotions. 
  Speaking to CRIME-PRESS on Friday, spokesman for Russian 
Federal Counter-Intelligence Service Aleksandr Mikhailov 
suggested an example of such sustained reaction the recent 
arrest of a major agent working for "a Western secret service" 
reported earlier this year by service Director Nikolay Golushko. 
As a result, attempts to recruit a number of high-ranking 
Russian officials have been prevented while the officials 
removed from their posts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

