<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Says No Lysenko-Ames Link </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802103094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0954 
GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 28 Feb (CRIME-PRESS) -- "Even if Ames really 
did work for us, what does [Aleksandr] Lysenko, who only came to 
the United States last summer, have to do with it?" Yuriy 
Kobaladze, head of the press bureau of the Foreign Intelligence 
Service, said in an interview with a CRIME-PRESS correspondent. 
After all, if one is to believe the FBI, the country the Ames 
started spying for was the old Soviet Union, and the 
surveillance over them began 10 months ago. 
  Moreover, for the first time in the history of relations 
between our countries, Aleksandr Lysenko was, as it were, an 
official resident of the Russian intelligence in the United 
States. He was introduced to the director of the CIA and to the 
U.S. Administration in this capacity and was involved in 
"cooperation" between the two special services in tackling 
issues of global significance which override the rivalry between 
the two intelligence services, such as the fight against 
international terrorism, the proliferation of weapons of mass 
destruction, and other issues. 
  Now, as a spokesman for the Russian Foreign Ministry has 
announced, Russia is forced to take countermeasures and hence 
expel a CIA employee. 

</TEXT>

