<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Foreign Minister Mamedov on Ames Case </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2702120794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1105 
GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2702120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Georgiy Shmelev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 27 Feb -- Georgiy Mamedov, the deputy 
foreign minister of the Russian Federation, is confident that 
"the Ames case" will not affect the Russian-U.S. relations. 
  After the conclusion of a working visit to Latin American 
countries, Georgiy Mamedov visited Washington where he was 
holding negotiations on the situation around Sarajevo and 
Russian-U.S. relations. Straight after his return to Moscow he 
said in an interview to an ITAR-TASS correspondent that "they 
touched on the question of 'the Ames case' but it is an 
exaggeration to say that I was a special representative on this 
matter." Georgiy Mamedov said that there is rather a big fuss 
in the United States over this matter, but he believes that a 
lot is unclear in this case -- Ames himself has not admitted to 
being guilty. 
  Georgiy Mamedov said that it is difficult to explain why the 
declaration of "the Ames case" has coincided in time with the 
critical situation over Sarajevo and with the declaration of the 
new initiative by Boris Yeltsin, the president of Russia. 
  The deputy minister noted that "we simply should calmly and 
in a balanced way sort all that out." 

</TEXT>

