<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Motives for U.S. `Furor' Over Ames Case Pondered </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2502152394 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 25 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2502152394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Ravil Mustafin: "What Lies Behind the Arrest of </F>
the Ames'"] 
  [Excerpts] CIA officer Aldrich Hazen Ames, 52, was 
arrested on his way to work. His wife Maria was arrested at 
home. The Ames are accused of spying for the former USSR and 
for Russia for nearly nine years. [passage omitted] 
  In principle the arrest of a foreign agent is not that rare 
an event in the invisible war the various special services have 
been waging among themselves for many centuries. But the arrest 
of the Ames caused, perhaps, an overreaction in the United 
States. In Moscow U.S. Ambassador Pickering made an official 
protest to Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Lavrov. In 
Washington Secretary of State Christopher asked those Russian 
diplomats who had been in contact with the Ames' to leave the 
United States quietly, as it were. President Clinton, who, as 
it happens, was aware that U.S. counterintelligence had had the 
Ames under surveillance for 10 months, ordered administration 
staffers to carry out a detailed analysis of the consequences of 
the spies' activities for U.S. national security. Some senators 
were calling for aid to Russia to be frozen. 
  According to our experts, there are several ways of 
explaining the ballyhoo in the United States over the arrest of 
the Ames. First and foremost it could be a wish on the part of 
the U.S. special services to obtain one-sided advantages in 
conducting intelligence on Russian territory. Actually, Russian 
intelligence is doing no more in America than U.S. intelligence 
is doing in Russia, according to one Foreign Intelligence 
Service representative. Incidentally, CIA Director James 
Woolsey has repeatedly stated that his department is keeping an 
extremely close eye on Russia. 
  It is not inconceivable that the Ames case got such heavy 
publicity in view of the exposure of more than 20 foreign, 
including U.S. intelligence agents in Russia last year. They 
included a Russian citizen, who, as Nikolay Golushko, director 
of the Federal Counterintelligence Service, said in an IZVESTIYA 
interview, had caused damage to Russian national security 
interests comparable to the damage caused by former GRU officer 
Penkovskiy, who was shot in 1963. 
  Some observers believe that the furor caused by the arrest 
of 
the Ames' is a kind of adverse reaction on the part of certain 
U.S. circles to the shift of emphasis in Russian policy in the 
Balkans. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38067 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov039_a_94017" </HT>


