<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputies' Visit to U.S. Unaffected by Ames Case </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502235794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1741 
GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2502235794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Borisenko] </F>
  [Text] Washington, 25 Feb -- The arrest of CIA staffer 
Aldrich Hazel Ames, who has been accused of spying for Russia, 
has "in no way affected" the visit to the United States of a 
group of Russian members of parliament and representatives of 
the law and order bodies, the ITAR-TASS correspondent learned 
from the head of the delegation, Mikhail Mityukov, first deputy 
chairman of the State Duma. 
  The group of Russian representatives, which is in the United 
States to learn about fighting organized crime and protecting 
intellectual property, has had meetings with high-ranking 
representatives of the FBI and the State Department. They were 
received by U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno and U.S. Commerce 
Secretary Ronald Brown. 
  "There have been no contacts on this problem, and in any 
case 
we are not empowered to hold meetings with anyone on these 
issues," Mityukov declared. "I think this isolated case should 
not sully the pretty friendly level of relations between our 
countries. It will be examined and studied by the appropriate 
bodies, both Russian and American, after which we shall be in 
possession of real information. I think this case is being too 
much politicized". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

