<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seeks More Precise Stance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502173694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1605 
GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2502173694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmilal Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 25 Feb -- My dream is that, pushing on from 
such an important moment in the Bosnian crisis as the initiative 
of the Russian president, a democratic consensus will start 
taking shape in the sphere of foreign policy, which would sever 
all extremist attempts, Vitaliy Churkin, the deputy foreign 
minister and the special representative of the Russian president 
in the conflict zone, said. Commenting at the request of an 
ITAR-TASS correspondent on today's decision of the Federation 
Council to allocate an additional military contingent for the UN 
forces, the diplomat stressed that we do not need confrontation 
and war, but we need a strong foreign policy based on a 
democratic consensus. Today's parliament decision, adopted at 
Yeltsin's request, will make it possible, he says, to hope that 
that is exactly how it will be. 
  Churkin reported that for the time being the issue of 
expanding the presence of Russian troops in other places is not 
on the agenda. In general, he thinks that the crisis over 
Sarajevo -- the behavior of the Russian side and of our Western 
partners, who are NATO members -- needs to be analyzed 
seriously. During the crisis our attempts to solve issues 
amicably with them did not always produce a response, the deputy 
minister noted. That is why now, he believes, we need to 
formulate our position more precisely and to defend it in an 
equally precise way. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

