<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Favors Strong Foreign Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502185094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1748 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502185094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 25 TASS -- "I favour the formation 
of a democratic consensus in foreign policy to prevent any 
extremist pronouncements. The consensus should proceed from the 
Russian president's initiative on the Bosnian settlement," 
Deputy Russian Foreign Minister and presidential envoy to the 
conflict zone Vitaliy Churkin said here today. 
  "We do not need war and confrontation, we need a strong 
foreign policy to be based on democratic consensus," said the 
diplomat commenting on ITAR-TASS request at today's decision of 
the Federation Council to assign additional troops to the U.N. 
forces. The decision taken on request of Boris Yeltsin will give 
hope to the consensus, he said. 
  In the words of Vitaliy Churkin, the question of expanded 
Russian presence in other areas has not been raised. 
  "We still have to analyze the crisis around Sarajevo -- the 
behavior of Russians and their Western partners, members of 
NATO," said Churkin. "Our attempts to peacefully settle 
problems of the crisis have not always been supported," he 
noted. "We should clearly outline our stand and keep to it," 
said Churkin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

