<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry `Closely Analyzing' Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802122094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1137 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802122094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Foreign Ministry is "closely analyzing" the 
situation following the downing of four combat planes belonging 
to the Bosnian Serbs Monday morning in the area of Banja Luka in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina by NATO aircraft, a senior Foreign Ministry 
official told Interfax on Monday. 
  As he said, Russia's Foreign Ministry sent an inquiry to the 
headquarters of the UN Protection Forces in the former 
Yugoslavia. "According to the preliminary data available to the 
headquarters, the Bosnian Serbs' planes were returning to their 
base after a bomb strike on a military plant controlled by 
Bosnian Muslims. If this is indeed the case, the Bosnian Serbs 
violated one of the UN Security Council's resolutions adopted 
more than a year ago. The resolution bans flights by military 
planes in the air space of Bosnia-Herzegovina," he said. 
  According to the diplomat, the "closed skies" resolution has 
been repeatedly violated by Bosnian Serbs, Muslims and Croats. 
"They all were aware of the possible "adequate military" 
measures toward "the violator." However such measures were not 
taken till today," he said. 
  Russian diplomats who scored in the past two weeks 
considerable successes on the road of settling the crisis in 
Bosnia by peaceful means had repeatedly warned the Serbs, Croats 
and Muslims against the possible provocations "by field 
commanders or whoever else," Interfax's interviewee pointed out. 
"Now what we warned against and what we feared has happened," he 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38082 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov039_a_94032" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-039 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
