<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Chief on Tasks Facing New Contingent in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2602141994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1100 
GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2602141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 26 Feb -- The Russian side has adopted the 
only correct stance in the settlement of the Bosnian conflict: 
"The best path to peace is the one that does not produce human 
casualties." This was stated at a news conference today by 
Colonel General Mikhail Kolesnikov, chief of the General Staff 
of the Russian Armed Forces. 
  The situation in the region of the conflict, the general 
said, remains complex. The NATO ultimatum on bombardments has 
not been lifted. An increase in forces is essential. This is 
why, at the suggestion of the Russian president, the Federation 
Council decided to send an additional contingent of Russian 
"blue helmets." 
  They have been given the task, Mikhail Kolesnikov said, of 
separating the opposing sides, preventing attempts to transfer 
heavy weapons to other parts of the Balkans, ensuring unhampered 
access to Sarajevo for humanitarian aid convoys, and creating 
conditions for the deployment of additional UN forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

