<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Contingent To Arrive in March </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2602155494 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1200 GMT 
26 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2602155494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia has begun to play a more independent role in 
the Bosnian conflict. The fulfillment by the Serbs of their 
commitments to withdraw heavy weapons from the vicinity of 
Sarajevo is, to a great extent, an act of trust in Russian 
policy in the region. According to our correspondent Marina 
Chernyukha, this was stated at a news conference in Moscow today 
by Mikhail Kolesnikov, chief of the General Staff of the Russian 
Armed Forces. He emphasized that compared with the Muslims' 
infantry the Serbian infantry now finds itself in a 
disadvantageous position. If the former want to seek revenge, 
it might have grave consequences. 
  The prevention of provocations by either side is the main 
task of the Russian blue helmets. It was noted at the briefing 
that the additional contingent of 300 servicemen will be 
arriving in Bosnia in March. 

</TEXT>

