<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soskovets in Norway, Discusses Oil </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2702225694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1830 
GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2702225694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Pshenichnikov] </F>
  [Excerpt] Lillehammer (Norway), 27 Feb -- Oleg Soskovets, 
first deputy head of the Russian Government, paying an official 
visit to Norway today met Norwegian Minister for the Economy, 
Oil Industry and Power Sector Jens Stoltenberg. 
  Oleg Soskovets told ITAR-TASS that the meeting focused on 
cooperation between the two countries to exploit offshore oil 
deposits. Norway has unique experience in this area and the 
future of the Russian generating industry lies precisely in this 
kind of extraction of oil and gas. A month ago, Russia and 
Norway signed a memorandum on cooperation in oilfield 
development. This is now being put into effect and a legal 
framework is being drawn up. Norway is interested in partnership 
with Russia and is planning close cooperation with it also as 
part of the European energy charter. Our interest is in 
management experience in oil and gas extraction with foreign 
investment, Oleg Soskovets stressed. 
  Commenting on the outcome of his meeting here on Saturday 
with Norwegian Foreign Minister Bjorn Godal, he said that Norway 
is closely following the reform process in Russia. The 
Norwegian foreign minister was told that no changes to the 
Russian government's reform policy are planned and that the 
reforms are irreversible. It was also stressed that Russia is 
in a special situation by virtue of its involvement in the CIS. 
This refers primarily to the credits for fuel purchases that 
Russia extends to CIS states because of economic and political 
circumstances. These credits are considerably more than the aid 
being planned by the G-7 and the IMF. This circumstance defines 
the specific nature of relations between Russia and the other 
CIS states, the first deputy prime minister emphasised. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

