<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Most Deputies Vote for Presidential Republic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2602105094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0550 
GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2602105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By BELINFORM correspondents Vladimir Glod, Larisa Lazar for </F>
TASS] 
  [Text] Minsk, 26 Feb -- It appears that on the first day of 
spring Belarus will change from being a parliamentary republic 
into a presidential republic. On the evening of 1 March the 
results will be announced of the secret vote by Belarus 
parliamentarians, with named voting slips, for or against 
introducing the institution of a presidency. And although 
officially the voting will end only at 1800 on 1 March, the 
BELINFORM correspondents have learned from confidential sources 
that 230 voting slips have already been deposited in the ballot 
boxes and 210 deputies have voted in favor of introducing the 
post of president as the head of state and executive authority. 
For this decision to receive the force of law it needs to 
gather another 22 votes. 
  About 100 parliamentarians have not yet received their 
voting 
slips. And even taking into account that 40 deputies have said 
that they will not vote, one can predict today with 99.9 percent 
certainty that Belarus will have a new state structure. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

