<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Denies Existence of Concentration Camps </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502140894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1326 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridneva] </F>
  [Text] Dushanbe February 25 TASS -- The Tajik Foreign 
Ministry has bluntly denied recent reports, appearing in the 
foreign press with references to the "International Amnesty" 
human rights organisation, that there are secret concentration 
camps on the territory of the republic. 
  Tajik Foreign Ministry's Department Chief Zafar Saidov told 
a 
briefing here today that not a single official representative of 
the foregoing human rights organisation had addressed such 
information to the Tajik Foreign Ministry or other state bodies 
over the past six months. 
  "The leadership of Tajikistan," the diplomat said, "have 
asked representatives of the mission of permanent U.N. 
observers, currently visiting the republic, to undertake a 
fact-finding trip to the spots, where these concentration camps 
are allegedly located, and to carry out the most careful 
investigation." 
  "For its part," Saidov stressed, "the Tajik leadership, 
which 
has always honoured all the international human rights acts and 
which is now busy building a democratic law-government state, 
believes that no goals can justify the use of tortures, physical 
violence and other actions humiliating human dignity, about 
which the foreign mass media have reported. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

