<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visiting PRC's Qiao Shi Defends Human Rights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2801150194 Vienna DIE PRESSE in German 28 Jan 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> AU2801150194 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DIE PRESSE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "China Is Not Yet Ready for a </F>
Renunciation of the Death Sentence"] 
  [Text] Vienna -- When the topic of human rights was 
broached during his visit to Vienna, Qiao Shi, president of 
China's parliament, referred to his country's history. 
  Even if human rights violations are painful, the dialogue 
must be continued, Parliament President Heinz Fischer stated 
after his meeting with Chinese Parliament President Qiao Shi. 
After a four-day visit to Germany and Switzerland, which was 
accompanied by protests, he arrived in Austria with a delegation 
of parliament deputies. Asked about the human rights situation 
and Tibet, Qiao Shi referred to China's history and the great 
significance of the preservation of political stability. 
Replying to Fischer's request to consider banning the death 
penalty, Qiao Shi stated that China is not yet ready for a 
renunciation of this type of punishment. 
  Marijana Grandits, foreign-policy spokeswoman for the 
Greens, 
described Qiao as "one of the most sinister figures of China's 
political landscape." If Austria does not oppose vehemently the 
systematic human rights violations, this means continuing the 
tradition of ignorant and opportunist policies. Exiled Tibetans 
demonstrated in front of the Chancellor's Office in 
Ballhausplatz. 

</TEXT>

