<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   French Minister Meets With Mock, Views EU Expansion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3001161894 Salzburg SALZBURGER NACHRICHTEN in German 29 
Jan 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU3001161894 </F>
<F P=104>  Salzburg SALZBURGER NACHRICHTEN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [SALZBURGER NACHRICHTEN report: "EU Enlargement, Then East </F>
Europe"] 
  [Excerpt] Vienna -- The European Union [EU] is envisaging 
the extension of the Community to East Europe more and more 
clearly. EU Commission President Jacques Delors stated in 
Brussels on Friday [28 January] that the work of his authority 
will focus on a concept for a "greater Europe." 
  These considerations also played a role at the 
Austrian-French forum that was held in the Vienna Town Hall on 
Friday at the invitation of Foreign Minister Mock and the City 
of Vienna. There Alain Lamassoure, French minister for European 
affairs, summarized the stage plan in the direction of 
pan-Europe: First the EU has to be increased to 16 members, so 
that Austria also belongs to it. Then four steps must follow: 
First, implementation of the Maastricht resolutions on foreign 
and security policy; second, subsidiarity; third, 
democratization; fourth, gradual integration of Central and East 
Europe. "We need a policy for the East," Lamassoure said. 
  He wants to start the EU's policy for the East with an 
"engagement day," that is, a basic offer to the East European 
states that permits them to become members of the Community. 
This policy must be extended to Russia. In the transition 
period there will be a security problem, with which Austria will 
cope best by acceding to the Western European Union (WEU), 
toward which the East European states are also pushing their 
way. Everything else would be paradoxical, he said. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

