<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy `Wants More Contacts' With German Right </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3101130294 Hamburg WELT AM SONNTAG in German 30 Jan 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> AU3101130294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg WELT AM SONNTAG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "H.V.": "Zhirinovskiy: More Contacts With </F>
German Rightists"] 
  [Text] Bonn -- The party leader of the Russian right-wing 
extremists, Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, wants to expand his direct 
contacts with the right-wing extremist German People's Union 
[DVU] in Germany to other rightist parties and groups. 
  According to information obtained by WELT AM SONNTAG, the 
Federal Government has received indications that another 
application for entry by Zhirinovskiy can be expected on the 
occasion of a "European Congress," which is to take place in 
Cologne at the beginning of February. On 29 December 1993 
Zhirinovskiy was refused an entry visa. 
  According to findings by the Federal Office for the 
Protection of the Constitution, the "European Congress" is being 
prepared by rightist German deputies of the European Parliament. 
According to findings by intelligence services, Zhirinovskiy 
intends to try to get intentional approval for his policy in 
Europe and to use his contacts with rightist German politicians 
for this purpose. At a joint press conference in Moscow this 
week, Zhirinovskiy assured DVU Chairman Gerhard Frey of "eternal 
friendship." On the same day, the Moscow public prosecutor's 
office initiated proceedings against Zhirinovskiy for war 
agitation. 

</TEXT>

