<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Denktas Sends Second Letter to UN Stating Position </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2901121694 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1100 
GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2901121694 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over still of Turkish Cypriot leader </F>
Rauf Denktas] 
  [Text] Rauf Denktas, president of the Turkish Republic of 
Northern Cyprus, sent a second letter to UN Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali, reiterating that the Turkish Cypriot side 
is ready to discuss the confidence-building measures concerning 
the Cyprus problem. 
  In his second letter, Denktas announced that the Turkish 
Cypriots accept in principle articles 37, 38, 42, and 43, which 
stipulate the transfer of Maras [Varosha] to UN administration 
and the opening of Lefkosa [NIcosia] Airport to traffic. In the 
letter, Denktas also declared that he is ready to discuss the 
implementation of the said articles with Greek Cypriot 
Administration leader Glavkos Kliridhis. 
  In a statement to TRT, Denktas charged that Kliridhis found 
himself in a difficult situation after the Turkish Cypriot side 
announced its readiness to discuss the confidence-building 
measures and sent a letter to Butrus-Ghali in an attempt to 
alter the agenda. Denktas pointed out that Kliridhis tried to 
eliminate the guarantee agreements by raising the proposal to 
demilitarize the island. 
  Denktas remarked that following this confusion, he asked Joe 
Clark, UN secretary general's special envoy for Cyprus, to 
clarify the matter and therefore wrote the second letter. 
Denktas added: There is no sense in solving the issue through 
statements without sitting at the negotiating table. As we have 
always stated, if a picture emerges from the negotiating table 
to the benefit of the Turkish Cypriot people, one that 
guarantees the interests and security of the Turkish Cypriots in 
line with the stipulations of the UN secretary general and the 
experts' reports, then our Assembly can say yes to this. If, 
however, such a picture does not emerge, then we can make a 
reassessment. Therefore, we stated and underlined our position 
once more. If the negotiations are to begin, then let them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

