<F P=100> Turkey </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Officials Warn of Economic Crisis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2801215894 Ankara TURKISH DAILY NEWS in English 25 Jan 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> NC2801215894 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TURKISH DAILY NEWS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara--Two of Turkey's top economic decision makers 
have warned that the economy is on the wrong track. 
  They added that an economic crisis might occur in the coming 
years as a result of monetary and fiscal imbalances. "Things 
have turned sour. I am afraid difficult times are ahead of us," 
one senior government economist told a TURKISH DAILY NEWS editor. 
  The same official, one of Prime Minister Tansu Ciller's 
closest economic aides, said that economic conditions have 
deteriorated so rapidly that the political authorities might 
soon be deadlocked. He spoke on condition of strict anonymity. 
In a related development, one senior monetary authority 
confirmed to the TURKISH DAILY NEWS that Turkey had no foreign 
currency shortages at the moment. However, he warned that if the 
present trend continues for another two years, the economy will 
have to confront a foreign currency crisis. 
  "The prime minister is right when she says there is no 
currency shortage in the economy. Yet the Turkish economy won't 
endure today's growing foreign account deficits for another two 
years," he said. He also asked not to be named. 
  The Turkish foreign trade gap climbed to an all-time high of 
$11.3 billion in the first 10 months of 1993, compared with the 
original program target of only $8.8 billion. 
  The current account deficit soared to $4.8 billion in the 
January-October period, making the prospect for the balance of 
payments a bleak one. 
  Prime Minister Tansu Ciller denies that Turkey has foreign 
currency problems. 
  She claimed that the economic management of the coalition 
government will start bearing fruit in 1995. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38180 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu020_q_94024" </HT>


