<F P=100> Turkey </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cetin, Clark Discuss Cyprus Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2801124694 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1100 
GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2801124694 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin has declared that the 
Cyprus problem cannot be resolved through Turkey's support 
alone. The same support, understanding, and courage must be 
displayed by Greece as well. Cetin met with Joe Clark, the UN 
secretary general's special envoy for Cyprus, in Istanbul this 
morning. 
  In a statement after the one-hour meeting, Cetin reported 
that the recent developments in Cyprus were discussed with 
Clark. Cetin recalled that in his letter to the UN secretary 
general, Rauf Denktas, president of the Turkish Republic of 
Northern Cyprus, announced that he accepts the 
confidence-building measures in principle. Cetin added: 
  [Begin Cetin recording] Kliridhis must do the same. The two 
leaders will meet and discuss the confidence-building measures. 
We want a viable and just solution for Cyprus. As in the past, 
the Turkish Government will continue to contribute to efforts 
made by Mr. Denktas on this subject. [end recording] 
  In turn, Clark remarked that the Denktas announcement that 
he 
accepts the confidence-building measures is an encouraging step. 
Clark noted that he does not doubt that Turkey and the United 
Nations share the same views on the Cyprus question. 
  After his meeting with Clark, Cetin left for the World 
Economic Forum meetings in Davos, Switzerland. 

</TEXT>

