<H3> <TI>   Discusses Turkmenistan Pipeline Project </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA3001164594 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1540 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA3001164594 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Davos, Jan 30 (A.A) -- Turkmenistan President 
Saparmurad Niyazov on Sunday [30 January] presented President 
Suleyman Demirel and Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin with the work 
on its oil and natural gas pipeline projects for evaluation and 
examination. 
  Speaking to an A.A. reporter following a breakfast he was 
hosting in honour of the heads of state of the Central Asian 
republics and Pakistan's Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto, Demirel 
said there are two possible routes for the pipeline, one being 
through Iran and Turkey, the other through the Caspian Sea, both 
reaching the Mediterranean. 
  Demirel said that Turkmenistan favours the first choice, 
adding that British, French, German and Turkish companies 
closely follow the developments concerning these project. 
  He said Turkey, in the coming years, will become one of the 
most important energy terminals in the world. 
  Kazakhstan President Nursultan Nazarbayev, Turkmenistan's 
Saparmurad Niyazov, Uzbekistan's Islam Karimov, and Pakistan's 
Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto attended the breakfast. 
  Following the meeting, Demirel received Israeli Foreign 
Minister Shim'on Peres. [passage omitted] 
  Demirel's scheduled meeting with Slovenia's Prime Minister 
Janez Drnovsek did not take place and was cancelled. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

