<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pakistan's Bhutto Meets Swedish, Mexican Leaders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2901150394 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2901150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Davos today, the prime minister, Ms. Benazir 
Bhutto, had meetings with the Swedish prime minister and the 
Mexican president. In her meeting with the Swedish prime 
minister, Mr. Carl Bildt, Ms. Benazir Bhutto greatly lauded the 
leading role played by Sweden in safeguarding human rights. PTV 
representative Jaafar Bilgrami reports that Ms. Benazir Bhutto 
briefed her Swedish counterpart about the prevailing situation 
in Kashmir and particularly mentioned the violation of human 
rights in the valley. She also discussed the situation in 
Afghanistan and Central Asia and reiterated that Pakistan would 
continue to work for bringing about peace. She also discussed 
the situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina and informed the Swedish 
prime minister about her forthcoming visit to Sarajevo, which 
she described as a symbol of solidarity with the people of 
Bosnia. She said Pakistan supports the UN efforts to send 
troops to Bosnia to have a peaceful settlement. 
  Discussing the bilateral cooperation, Ms. Benazir Bhutto 
expressed the hope that Sweden will assist Pakistan in (Bhimari) 
Tunnel project which may open new vistas of closer cooperation 
with Central Asian republics. The Swedish prime minister, Carl 
Bildt, greatly appreciated her participation in Davos conference 
and welcomed the socioeconomic program of her government for 
development and progress. 
  Pakistan's prime minister also held a meeting with the 
president of Mexico, Mr. Carlos Salinas. She briefed the 
Mexican president about the Kashmir issue, the Pakistan-U.S. 
relations, and internal and external policies of Pakistan. She 
congratulated the Mexican president on NAFTA agreement and asked 
him not to discriminate [against] the Third World countries. 
The Mexican president assured the prime minister that special 
care will be taken for comprehensive GATT regulations and also 
to safeguard the economic and trade interests of the developing 
countries. Later, talking to PTV representative, the Mexican 
president said: 
  [Begin Salinas recording] It was a very positive meeting 
because we were able to discuss the bilateral relationship and 
also issues of interest for the prime minister, issues relating 
to Pakistan and also the perspective of our stronger trade 
relations; and I told her that NAFTA, the North American Free 
Trade Agreement, does not create a fortress-like trading area, 
but is open to the participation of other countries as trading 
partners or even as members. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

