<H3> <TI>   Czech Premier Meets Danish, Finnish Counterparts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3001094194 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 0800 
GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3001094194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus held talks with 
Danish and Finnish prime ministers at the World Economic Forum 
in Davos yesterday. During the talks, Prime Minister Klaus 
distanced himself from the opinion voiced by Finnish Prime 
Minister Esko Aho, according to whom the emergence of large 
European companies might help in coping with American and Asian 
economic competition. Prime Minister Klaus rejected this idea 
pertaining, according to him, to the fifties and sixties, saying 
that small companies are more competitive than clumsy and 
bureaucratic colossi. 
  Later on during the talks, Klaus said that talks between 
current and future members of the European Union had revealed 
unanimity in many areas, as well as some fine differences of 
opinion in some others. According to him, the Czech Republic 
can enrich European integration thanks to its experience from 
the former regime. West Europe does not share this past, and 
therefore it does not perceive some of the matters so sharply. 

</TEXT>

