<H3> <TI>   Swiss-EU Ties Viewed; Peres-'Arafat Talks Set </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2901152994 Bern Swiss Radio International in English 1500 
GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2901152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern Swiss Radio International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Swiss foreign minister Flavio Cotti says talks with 
the leaders of Germany, Belgium, Finland, and Denmark have 
created a better climate for bilateral relations with the 
European Union [EU]. Mr. Cotti was speaking after discussions 
on the third day of the World Economic Forum in the Swiss resort 
of Davos. 
  Switzerland has been negotiating for closer relations with 
the EU following its rejection of membership of the European 
Economic Area in 1992. 
  Meanwhile, the Mexican president, Carlos Salinas De Gortari, 
has appealed to the forum for investment in his country. He 
described the uprising of indigenous rebels in the southern 
state of Chiapas as a local problem in a region of deep poverty, 
and said the government was determined to reach a political 
solution. 
  The highlight of the forum is shortly due to take place, 
when 
Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres meets Palestine Liberation 
Organization leader Yasir 'Arafat. The two men will discuss how 
to resolve differences over the Palestinian autonomy accord. 

</TEXT>

