<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kohl, Aho Discuss Finland's EU Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2801200794 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1700 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2801200794 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Esko Aho and German Federal 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl agree that Finland's European Union [EU] 
membership negotiations should be concluded within the agreed 
timeframe, that is before 1 March. Aho met Kohl in the ski 
resort of Davos in Switzerland, where they are taking part in 
the World Economic Forum, an informal meeting of world leaders. 
Aho explained the negotiating situation from Finland's point of 
view and emphasized the two central demands: Getting a permanent 
subsidy for northern agriculture and financing this subsidy from 
EU funds, not from Finland's state funds. 
  Kohl did not comment in detail on Finland's goals but gave 
the assurance that Germany is very much aware of them. Earlier 
today Kohl said that it is important that Finland, Norway, 
Sweden and Austria join the EU from the beginning of next year. 
  Aho will remain in Davos until Sunday [30 January] and will 
meet several European leaders, among others Russian Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. 

</TEXT>

