<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jail To Be Built for Former Yugoslavia War Criminals </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2801090394 Paris AFP in English 0633 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2801090394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Hague, Jan 28 (AFP) -- The United Nations is 
to build a jail here for suspected war criminals from the former 
Yugoslavia, a senior Italian judge told AFP. 
  The slammer is being built inside a prison here and will 
consist of 12 cells, each with a minimal floor space of seven 
square metres (74 square feet). 
  Suspects will appear before the International Court on 
Crimes 
in the Former Yugoslavia, the court's president Antonio Cassese 
said. 
  "The new cells should be handed over to us at the end of 
June," Cassese said, adding that a new international penal code 
would have to be drawn up to regulate the prison. 
  Dutch police will be responsible for transferring the 
prisoners to and from the jail but, once inside, their security 
and that of the court's judges will fall to armed UN guards. 
  Sentences handed down by the court will be served in the 
prisons of UN member states. France and Italy have already 
offered to take in some of those convicted. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

