<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delors: EC To Rethink Policies on East Europe </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2801181094 Paris AFP in English 1801 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2801181094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Jan 28 (AFP) -- The European Community is 
about to embark on a fundamental rethink of its relations with 
East and Central Europe, European Commission President Jacques 
Delors said here Friday [28 January]. 
  In an address to journalists, he acknowledged that the 
European Community lacked vision in dealing with the region and 
that its executive intended to embark on a process of 
"self-criticism" to map out a new policy. 
  "The Community must delve into the roots of its history," he 
said, adding that "Vienna, Budapest, Warsaw and other cities are 
as much poles of our cultural identity as Berlin, Paris, 
Brussels, Amsterdam or London." 
  The European Community has negotiated association agreements 
with Poland, Hungary, the Czech and Slovak Republics, Romania 
and Bulgaria which are supposed to prepare the way for these 
countries to enter the European Community. 
  But the applicants have been given no timetable for entry, 
or 
any assurance that they can expect to enter the Community before 
the turn of the century. 
  The European Community has also been blamed for holding up 
the economic development of these countries by maintaining 
barriers to some of their most vigorous exports such as steel 
and agricultural products. 
  The European Community's chief executive said the Commission 
intended to launch an analysis of all existing EC aid, 
particularly economic and technological, to East Europe. 
  Delors is to give up his post as European Commission 
president at the end of this year. He has occupied the post 
since 1985. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

