<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   World Economic Forum Session Continues in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   FRG Official: Lower Interest Rates </H4>
<F P=102> AU2801163394 Paris AFP in English 1618 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2801163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Davos, Switzerland, Jan 28 (AFP) -- The German 
Bundesbank is ready under certain conditions to lower its 
official interest rates and still has some margin to reduce 
long-term rates, a senior official said Friday [28 January]. 
  Gerd Haller, German secretary of state for finance, said at 
the World Economic Forum here that the Bundesbank's action 
depends on the evolution of Germany's monetary supply and wage 
negotiations. 
  "The Bundesbank is prepared to bring down short-term 
interest 
rates, but it depends on other factors," Haller said. 
  He said that although long-term rates are at an historic 
low, 
"there is still some room for long-term interest rates to go 
down." 
  Germany is under pressure from its European partners to 
lower 
its interest rates, seen as a source of currency instability in 
and a damper on efforts to stimulate economic growth on the 
continent. 
  British Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke, whose 
country jumped from the European Community currency grid in 
September of 1992, said the European Community needs monetary 
stability to make its single market work. 
  "What we need in the European Community is exchange-rate 
stability if we are to get the best out of the single market," 
he said. 
  Clarke said the best means of assuring this is making 
efforts 
to bring the various economies closer, adding, "We need to make 
sure we coordinate what we are doing." 
  "The challenge will be to keep, as we come out of the 
recession, the stability of exchange rates that we have at the 
moment," he said. 

</TEXT>

