<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   World Economic Forum Session Continues in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   Czech's Klaus: Build Europe of Citizens </H4>
<F P=102> LD2901142994 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1300 
GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2901142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus delivered one 
of the main addresses at today's World Economic Forum session in 
Davos. Our correspondent Jiri Halousek reports: 
  [Halousek] [Passage omitted] Addressing the working group on 
the issues concerning the admission of new members to European 
institutions, the Czech prime minister stressed that the future 
status of Europe in the world does not depend so much on the 
existence and activities of multilateral European institutions 
as on the quality and structure of the political, social, and 
economic systems in individual countries. In this context 
Vaclav Klaus spoke in favor of abandoning bureaucratic measures 
and unnecessary state interventions. He said that it is 
necessary to build a Europe of citizens and not a Europe of 
politicians. The Czech Republic, as well as all other Central 
European countries, has always considered itself to be a part of 
Europe and, thus, would not like to be deprived of advantages 
ensuing from membership in European institutions. I firmly 
believe, continued Vaclav Klaus, that my country has crossed 
already the Rubicon between the two totally different political, 
social, and economic systems, and that it is ready to take 
further steps toward a reasonable European integration. 
However, by this term I do not mean a total integration. 
  The Czech Republic does not want to be always the recipient 
and it is prepared to offer something. According to Vaclav 
Klaus, we are aware of the fact that we have to solve our 
problems ourselves and we do not expect Europe to solve them for 
us. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

