<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgium's Dehaene on Solutions to Labor Problems </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR3101134594 Groot-Bijgaarden DE STANDAARD in Dutch 31 Jan 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> BR3101134594 </F>
<F P=104>  Groot-Bijgaarden DE STANDAARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed JB: "Sweden Controlling Crisis of its </F>
Welfare State, Belgium Still at Odds With It"] 
  [Excerpts] Davos -- It was a dubious honor yesterday. The 
prime ministers of Sweden and Belgium were sitting on the 
platform with a select group of businessmen as their audience; 
the theme was the future of the welfare state. [passage omitted] 
  Prime Minister Dehaene, who claimed he was speaking from a 
Belgian and European point of view, emphasized that the share of 
social security in national income, has reached "the highest 
possible level." In his opinion, we must define the social 
adjustments we deem necessary, within a European context. The 
biggest challenge will be to preserve social security and to 
prevent a dual society from being formed, in which part of the 
population would become marginal. 
  He believes that the problems on the labor market must be 
dealt with on three levels: A liberalization of the excessively 
stringent rules, which keep employers from hiring people, a 
substitution of unemployment pay by an active policy of training 
and by an obligation to accept jobs, and a reduction of wage 
costs, especially those of unskilled workers, by trying to find 
alternative financing for social security. 
  Dehaene also believes that the labor unions and employers' 
organizations are still too much a reflection of the situation 
in the period of industrialization. This pursuit of uniform 
regulations for everyone, which was inherited from the past, 
thwarts the necessary flexibility. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

