<H3> <TI>   Swiss Official Opens World Economic Forum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR3101143194 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1705 GMT 27 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR3101143194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed ZS; GC: "Mr. Delamuraz Opens 24th Davos </F>
Forum: Appeal for National Policies That Are More Open To 
World"; as released by Bern ATSA/SDAA database] 
  [Text] Davos, 27 Jan (ATS) -- Economic and political 
officials can no longer be content with taking care of business 
at home. Markets and economic activities are becoming more 
global at an increasingly fast rate. "Our national economic 
policies must be adjusted to these realities," said Jean-Pascal 
Delamuraz Thursday evening [27 January] at the opening of the 
24th Davos Forum, in the company of Helmut Kohl and Nestle 
President Helmut Maucher. 
  The [Swiss] Federal Council member felt that the current 
globalization is "the most striking" development of the late 
20th century. The drawing together of human groups is, however, 
nothing new. "In fact it goes all the way back to man's 
discovery of flint," Mr. Delamuraz said. 
  However, the pace at which the phenomenon is accelerating is 
unprecedented. "And we were not prepared for it," continued the 
head of the Federal Department of the Public Economy (DFEP). A 
firm or a market both tend to be attached to a given country. 
"Our economic policies are still largely geared toward this 
national perception." 
<H5>  Rapid European Integration </H5>
  German Chancellor Helmut Kohl appealed for a "quick paced" 
pursuit of European integration, five months before Germany 
takes over the EC presidency. He agreed with Mr. Delamuraz in 
stressing the need for increasing the convergence of the 
European states' national policies. 
  "Only in this way will we obtain all the fruits of economic 
and monetary union," said Mr. Kohl, who was also in favor of 
increased openness in world trade. 
  Support for the new democracies of East Europe must be 
renewed, continued the chancellor. The failure of the reforms 
would be catastrophic, whereas success would offer the only 
chance for peaceful coexistence in Europe. 
<H5>  Bilateral Meetings </H5>
  A number of figures combined their trip to Switzerland for 
the Davos Forum with meetings with Swiss officials. Swiss 
President Otto Stich was to meet Thursday evening with Uzbek 
President Islam Karimov at the Lohn residence. 
  Flavio Cotti, the head of the Federal Department of Foreign 
Affairs (DFAE), met Thursday in Bern with Madagascar Prime 
Minister Francisque Ravony and in Kloten with Danish Foreign 
Minister Niels Helveg Petersen. 
<H5>  'Arafat in Bern </H5>
  On Thursday, the DFAE stressed the importance of the first 
meeting ever between Yasir 'Arafat, Otto Stich, and Flavio Cotti 
planned for Monday in Bern. In doing so, Switzerland is 
demonstrating its desire to continue making a contribution to an 
"irreversible" peace process. 
  In the meantime, Flavio Cotti is to meet on Friday in Bern 
with Egyptian Foreign Minister 'Amr Mussa, and in Davos with his 
Israeli counterpart, Shim'on Peres. Mr. Peres and Mr. 'Arafat 
will hold talks in Davos, which will be the most awaited moment 
of the Forum. 
  Mr. Delamuraz is to hold talks on Saturday in Davos with 
Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto and European Commission 
Vice President Leon Brittan, and on Sunday with Russian Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. 
<H5>  Number of Participants Reaches Maximum </H5>
  Some 1,200 figures from politics, economics, the arts, and 
the sciences from more than 70 countries signed up for the 24th 
Forum on the world economy in Davos. They will be able to 
participate in some 500 sessions. 
  The number of participants was limited and the number of 
journalists was restricted to 200. Among the figures expected 
to attend, Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland, who 
is not well, had to cancel her visit to Davos. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

