<H3> <TI>   Further on Davos Activities </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR3101130994 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1501 GMT 30 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR3101130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed AZ: "Two Federal Council Members Visit the </F>
Davos Forum This Weekend -- Talks Dominated by GATT and 
Relations With European Union"; as released by Bern ATSA/SDAA 
database] 
  [Text] Davos, 30 Jan (ATS) -- Federal Council members 
Jean-Pascal Delamuraz and Flavio Cotti extended their bilateral 
contacts this weekend in Davos, on the occasion of the [World] 
Economic Forum. For Mr. Cotti, head of the Federal Department 
of Foreign Affairs [DFAE], the talks focused on relations 
between Switzerland and the European Union [EU]. Meanwhile, Mr. 
Delamuraz was involved in discussions on the implementation of 
the GATT agreements. 
  Concluded in mid-December after seven years of negotiations, 
the Uruguay Round agreements ought to take effect as from 1 
January 1996. "That is the majority opinion emerging in Davos," 
commented Mr. Delamuraz on Sunday [30 January], at the end of 
his attendance at the World Economic Forum (WEF). In 
Switzerland, this deadline for ratification is "tight," the 
federal councillor said during an interview with the ATSA 
database. 
  "The package of around 30 agreements that I will be signing 
on behalf of Switzerland in Marrakesh in April will only be 
available in French, Spanish, and English," explained the head 
of the Federal Department of Public Economy [DFEP]. Now, the 
Federal Council will wait until the official German version of 
the EU is available before it launches the consultation 
procedure. 
  "I was struck by the extremely lucid discussions that took 
place this year among the Forum's participants," the head of the 
DFEP pointed out, summing up his visit. Mr. Delamuraz mainly 
discussed the future of GATT with the 20 or so leading world 
figures whom he met there. 
<H5>  Promising Development </H5>
  Before leaving Davos, Mr. Delamuraz particularly stressed 
the 
Swiss interest in those zones undergoing rapid economic 
development. On Friday, the Federal Council member had given a 
dinner for several members and heads of governments of Southeast 
Asia. "The ASEAN zone is one of the most promising areas for the 
Swiss economy," he said. On Saturday, Mr. Delamuraz also hosted 
a dinner in honor of an Argentine delegation led by Foreign 
Minister Domingo Cavallo. 
  The head of the DFEP also made the most of the presence in 
Davos of his Spanish, French, and Egyptian counterparts to 
exchange views with them bilaterally. Nor did Mr. Delamuraz 
neglect the countries of East Europe. In particular, he met 
with Bulgarian Prime Minister Lyuben Berov, Czech Prime Minister 
Vaclav Klaus, and head of the Russian Government Viktor 
Chernomyrdin. 
<H5>  Swiss-EU Relations </H5>
  On Friday and Saturday, Federal Council member Flavio Cotti 
was in Davos, where he discussed relations between Switzerland 
and the EU. He met with the heads of the German, Belgian, and 
Finnish Governments to discuss this topic, as well as with the 
Danish foreign minister. Both Belgium's Jean-Luc Dehaene and 
Denmark's Niels Petersen welcomed the Swiss strategic objective 
-- to join the EU in the medium term -- as a measure of 
confidence. 
  On Friday, Mr. Cotti held talks on the Middle East with his 
Israeli and Egyptian counterparts, Shim'on Peres and 'Amr Musa, 
respectively. The Federal Council member expressed the hope 
that the meeting between Mr. Peres and PLO leader Yasir 'Arafat 
would relaunch the peace process. Mr. Cotti was due to meet 
with the Palestinian leader in Bern on Monday, accompanied by 
President of the Swiss Confederation Otto Stich. 
  The chief of Swiss diplomacy took advantage of his presence 
in Davos to meet the South African delegation, during which the 
situation in that country before the first general elections, 
scheduled for 27 April was discussed. Switzerland feels 
committed to work side by side with countries undergoing an 
historical development, Mr. Cotti emphasized. The elimination 
of racial problems in South Africa is one of the main 
preoccupations of the DFAE. 

</TEXT>

