<H3> <TI>   Poland's Kwasniewski Pledges Continuing Reform Program </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3001205094 Warsaw PAP in English 2039 GMT 30 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD3001205094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Davos, Switzerland, Jan. 30 -- The ruling coalition 
is pledged to continue the programme of reform, and economic 
growth and financial discipline take precedence over social 
programmes, Aleksander Kwasniewski, leader of the Democratic 
Left Alliance, assured participants at the World Economic Forum 
in the Swiss resort of Davos at the weekend. 
  Kwasniewski insisted that "the government's priority is the 
development of the economy and the growth of gross domestic 
product. The main elements of reform are to be, and must be, 
continued. There is no other road for our country to reach 
democracy, the market economy and an integrated Europe." 
  He described the September 1993 election victory by leftist 
parties as proof of the maturity of the Polish political system, 
and not as a rejection of the process of reform. However, the 
result showed that personal hopes and expectations were also 
important. 
  Kwasniewski stressed that the government was seeking to 
maintain a very disciplined budgetary policy. He hoped that it 
might be possible to increase pensions and other social 
programmes, but only when the state had first earned the 
financial resources for those aims. At the moment, however, it 
was impossible to fund all such programmes, he said. 

</TEXT>

