<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Czech Trade Minister Outlines EBRD Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3101151494 Prague CTK in English 1137 GMT 31 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU3101151494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Davos Jan 31 (CTK) -- The European Bank for 
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) wants to participate in 
the financing of selected infrastructure projects in the Czech 
Republic and cooperate more closely with its banking sector, 
Vladimir Dlouhy, the Czech minister for industry and trade, said 
today. 
  Dlouhy, at the World Economic Forum where he met with EBRD 
President Jacques de Larosiere and his colleagues, added that 
the institution wanted to support the Czech Republic's 
"pro-export" policy through cooperating with the government's 
Export Guarantee and Insurance Agency, EGAP. 
  Larosiere is much more interested in specific projects than 
his predecessor, Jacques Attalli, Dlouhy said. The EBRD could, 
for instance, be less adverse to risks and make the policy of 
Czech banks more flexible by investing in their shares. 
  Dlouhy went on to say that the Czech Republic had managed to 
install the fundamental elements of a market economy while 
keeping its macroeconomic stability high and unemployment low, 
and achieving a change in its export orientation. 
  The country will now be rated by its economic growth, as are 
other countries with a market economy, Dlouhy said. "Growth is 
becoming the basic thing for us." 

</TEXT>

