<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Czech Premier Klaus Addresses Davos Session </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3101103394 Prague CTK in English 2208 GMT 28 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU3101103394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Davos, Jan 28 (CTK ) -- Most of the tasks now faced 
by the Czech Republic are already of a posttransformation 
nature, Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus said at a press conference 
held on the occasion of the World Economic Forum [WEF]. 
  He said that the country has already crossed the line 
dividing the old and new political, social and economic systems. 
To put it in medical terminology, the operation is over, but 
the patient may be still be in a rehabilitation center curing 
his muscles, Klaus added. 
  He predicted a 2-3 percent economic growth for the Czech 
Republic this year. Inflation is expected to decrease to a 
one-digit rate, which would be the first case in postcommunist 
Europe, Klaus said and added that unemployment would probably 
slightly grow above the present 3.5 percent. 
  He said that the Czech Republic did not need foreign loans, 
but on the contrary, the influx of foreign capital hampers 
currency policy management. 

</TEXT>

