<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Inter-European Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU To Promote Development of Democracy in East Europe </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2601093394 Brussels EUROPE in English 24 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2601093394 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels EUROPE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Commission Launches Second Program </F>
for Democracy in the East"; as released by Brussels TEXTLINE 
database] 
  [Text] The European Commission announced the launch of its 
second Democracy program for Central and East European 
countries, for a total of ECU12 million, this is: 

  -  The 
second program of its type under the PHARE [Economic 
Reconstruction Aid for Poland and Hungary] program, for ECU8 
million, benefiting 11 Central and East European countries; 
  -  A 
first program of the same type for countries of the former USSR, 
for ECU2 million, in the framework of the TACIS [CIS Technical 
Assistance] program (Mongolia, while covered by TACIS, is not 
involved in the program). 
  You will recall that a European Parliament initiative lies 
at 
the origin of these programs, aimed at promoting the development 
of democratic societies based on the rule of law and the 
expression of the free will of the citizens. The current 
program consists above all in a support for selected local 
nongovernmental organizations, through partnerships between them 
and similar organization in states of the Union. Thus, projects 
covering a wide range of activities (but not political party 
activities, nor capital expenditure, nor grants for conferences) 
will be able to benefit from subsidies of up to ECU150,000, 
which could be funded to the tune of 70 percent of the costs of 
each project. One of the conditions, however, is that the 
projects need at least three partners, two from the European 
Union and one from the beneficiary state. Moreover, ECU1 
million extra is planned for those countries benefiting from the 
PHARE [Economic Reconstruction Aid for Poland and Hungary], with 
view to financing a new aspect of the Program for Democracy, 
i.e. micro-projects: In this case, the subsidies from the 
European Union -- from ECU3,000 to ECU10,000 -- can finance up 
to 90 percent of the cost of the projects, and partnership with 
European Union organizations are not necessary. The European 
Commission will be assisted in the management of the programs by 
the European Human Rights Foundation, which has a lot of 
experience in similar programs undertaken by nongovernmental 
organizations [NGOs] which work to promote human rights and 
democracy. Thus, the Commission will select the projects and 
the Foundation will then follow their implementation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

