<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   CSCE Meeting: EC To Aid States Hit by Yugo-Sanctions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3101171894 Paris AFP in English 1647 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU3101171894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, Jan 31 (AFP) -- The EC said it was offering 
ECU100 million ($112 million) to help countries hit by the 
international embargo on the former Yugoslavia as a CSCE meeting 
on the issue opened here Monday [31 January]. 
  The two-day meeting, called by the Conference on Security 
and 
Cooperation in Europe (CSCE) ministerial conference in Rome last 
December, is discussing ways of helping countries such as 
Albania, Bulgaria, Croatia, Macedonia, Hungary, Romania and 
Ukraine which have been hard hit by the UN-imposed sanctions. 
  The European Community offer, in line with its programme of 
economic assistance to East Europe, aims to help set up a 
special transit corridors between these countries for trading. 
  The corridors, which could be set up next summer, would 
include special customs clearance at borders for priority-rated 
heavy goods vehicles. 
  One corridor could link Austria to Greece and Turkey, 
another 
Albania, Romania, Bulgaria and the Ukraine. 
  Each of the countries would offer special border crossing 
facilities to speed up the movement of non-Yugoslav-related 
freight. 
  An international conference might be held to organize the 
details of such a set up. 
  The European Commission has also suggested looking for new 
routes around Yugoslavia to free up present clogged roads. 
  Countries affected by the embargo either border Serbia and 
Montenegro -- under UN sanctions because of their perceived role 
in fomenting the war in Bosnia-Herzegovina -- or are affected by 
restrictions on traffic on the River Danube. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

