<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   World Economic Forum Continues in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   Mukherjee: India `Huge' Global Market </H4>
<F P=102> BK0102101794 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0102101794 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The commerce minister, Mr. Pranab Mukherjee, says 
the world business community is keen on investing in India. He 
said with a fully developed industrial base and trained manpower 
of 3.8 million scientists and technically qualified people, the 
foreign investment in India is bound to grow. Mr. Mukherjee, 
who is in Davos to attend the World Economic Forum meeting met 
several world economic leaders. Our correspondent Sudarshanam 
understands that Mr. Mukherjee also had four sessions with 
various businessmen and industrialists. In these meetings he 
made it clear that the economic liberalization initiated by the 
government is irreversible. He pointed out that India has a huge 
market to offer to the investors which is unmatched in any part 
of the globe. 
  Speaking on global urbanization in Davos, the Maharashtra 
chief minister, Mr. Sharad Pawar, called for more funds to help 
developing countries counter the adverse implications of 
urbanization in health and education. Mr. Pawar urged the 
developed countries to encourage research and training to 
reconcile city growth with healthy environment. He proposed the 
setting up of satellite towns to decentralize development and 
information, and said entertainment be brought by satellites to 
remote areas so that migration to cities can be checked. Mr. 
Pawar is participating in the World Economic Forum meeting at 
the invitation of the organizers. 

</TEXT>

