<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Company Ships Artillery Shell Factory to Turkey </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3101183694 Hamburg DER SPIEGEL in German 31 Jan 94 p 55 </F>
<F P=103> AU3101183694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DER SPIEGEL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Shell Factory Dispatched to Turkey"] </F>
  [Text] In the middle of January, a complete weapons 
factory produced by the German-Dutch defense company Eurometaal 
was transported by truck from Liebenau in Lower Saxony to 
Turkey. The factory is to be assembled in Kirikkale by German 
and Turkish specialists and is to be used for the production of 
large caliber artillery shells that have a splinter effect. The 
Economics Ministry, which is responsible for authorizing such 
exports, only approved the export of the factory to the 
Netherlands. As recently as 1992, the Bonn-based Federal 
Security Council rejected an application from the Eurometaal 
subsidiary in Liebenau to export 18,000 special shells to 
Turkey. The main reason was that it could not be ruled out that 
the ammunition would be used against Kurdish rebels. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38306 </DOCNO>
